It doesn't lower rewards to subnet owners, it just changes the splits. Global TAO economic weight gets 50% of the emissions and 50% to local dTAO. So if 90% stake to root 45% of the emissions goes to those holders but the remaining 55% is split among the holders in dTAO (the remaining 10%). Subnet owners are holders of their dTAO token. So on average the holders in dTAO would be making 11x a holder in root. Of course it has risk of dTAO price changes.
"So on average the holders in dTAO would be making 11x a holder in root." - can you elaborate on this, I'm not sure I'm following you there

emissions are calculated as 50% based on your global stake and 50% based on your dTAO stake for each subnet. So if 90% of people stake to root 90%*50%+0%*50%=45% of emissions for every subnet. The remaining 10% would therefore have 55% of the emissions across all subnets based on their dTAO stake in each calculated as Global TAO stake%*50%+local dTAO stake%*50%. 90% of Tao holders share 45% of the emissions and 10% share in 55% of the emissions. A 1% holder in all dTAO tokens would make 11X the emissions in dTAO that a 1% holder in root would make, but would be subject to price changes in dTAO.

I believe this is one of the most important aspects of dTAO that makes participation in the subnets much more likely over time than many are thinking right now. There is a big economic advantage to those who participate but it does come with risk.

Explanation below:

Introduction of "R" in emission distribution.

Assumptions:
- Currently emissions is 18:41:41 for subnet:validators:miners respectively. Whereby validators set the % allocation to subnets and as such also set the % allocation to the mining rewards per subnet.
- no bug hunt bounties (incentives) for quick reporting and fix.
- Subnet owners are the first to mine their own subnet.
- Subnets don't have a clear incentive to make transparent mining documentation

Proposal goal:
- increase bug hunt bounty funding for subnets.
- decrease meta gaming over bug report and fix
- increase efficacy of mining rewards.
- increase transparency on competitive mining
- increase competitive mining on a subnet
- increase subnet responsibility of playing fair
- increase clarity on mining documentation per subnet

My proposal for change below:
- addition of "R" in the emission distribution equation of the subnet allocated "41%:miners emission".
- "R" directly impacts the rewards for miners within the subnet, as well as the rewards for the subnet itself.
- each subnet to set "R" for their own subnet,
- R:1 means zero reward allocation to miners, R:0 implies full allocation to miners, R can be any number from 0 to 1
- unallocated mining rewards are recycled. 

Formulea:
- 18:41:41 for subnet:validators:miners
Becomes:
- 18+R/2:41:41-R, with R/2 recycled for subnet:validators:miners:recycling

Example:
Subnet ID    Mining ratio       Validator allocation
sn 1                25%           2%
sn 2        100%           5%
sn 3        50%           10%

Additional subnet rewards sn1:
- subnet reward: emission x 18% x 2%
- additional subnet mining rewards: emission x 41% x 2% x [50% x (1-25%)]
- mining rewards: emission x 41% x 2% x 25%
- additional recycling: emission x 41% x[(1-25%) x 50%)

Conclusion adding "R":
- "R" gives subnets funding for bug hunt bounties.
- "R" reduces metagaming as bounties increase bug reports and fixes.
- "R" gives subnets addition funding during bootstrapping phase.
- "R" reduces incentive subnets to mine own subnet
- increase subnet transparency on allocation of emissions (proper use of funds)
- additional recycling of emissions to use as resources for when subnets and/or miners are more competitive or evolved.
